  "timeframe": "1D / 1H / 15m",
  "market_context": "On ETH daily chart, price swept a low and closed back inside, with equal highs above acting as a buy-side liquidity target. Daily bias is bullish expansion toward those equal highs.",
  "key_observation": "The hourly T-Spot was too large for a positional entry due to poor risk-to-reward, so the analyst dropped to 15-minute to find a bearish fair value gap inversion as a refined entry trigger toward the equal highs target.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the daily chart, identified equal highs above as a target and noted a sweep with a close back inside, anticipating expansion on the next candle.",
    "Step 2: Dropped to the hourly time frame and identified the T-Spot, but determined it was too large for a positional entry as the stop below the lows would not provide adequate risk-to-reward.",
    "Step 3: Waited for price to reach back into the T-Spot, noting price was leaving the equal highs target intact, which preserved the bullish setup.",
    "Step 4: Dropped to the 15-minute time frame within the T-Spot and identified a bearish fair value gap that price inverted, providing the first refined entry trigger.",
    "Step 5: After missing the first entry, identified a second 15-minute inversion and took a retest entry, since a direct entry would not yield 2R to the equal highs target.",
    "Step 6: Both inversion-based entries delivered 2R because the higher time frame bias toward the equal highs was correct."
  ],
  "outcome": "Both 15-minute inversion entries reached the 2R target toward the equal highs.",
  "lessons": "The fractal model scales across time frames: when the immediate confirmation timeframe is too large for clean risk-to-reward, drop one more time frame to find an inversion entry. Context (HTF bias and target) must precede pattern recognition.",
